                        </div>
                      </div>

                      <p id="fs-idp135749488">
                        The change of one type of matter into another type (or the inability to change) is a
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="c"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >chemical property</span>. Examples of chemical properties include flammability, toxicity, acidity, and many other types of reactivity. Iron, for example, combines with oxygen in the presence of water to form rust; chromium does not oxidize (
                        <a
                          class="autogenerated-content"
                          href="#CNX_Chem_01_03_Rust"
                        >Figure 1.19</a>). Nitroglycerin is very dangerous because it explodes easily; neon poses almost no hazard because it is very unreactive.
                      </p>

                      <div class="os-figure" id="CNX_Chem_01_03_Rust">
                        <figure
                          class="scaled-down"
                          data-id="CNX_Chem_01_03_Rust"
                        >
